
[1]inveterate

   INVET'ERATE, a. [L. inveteratus, invetero; in and vetero, from vetus,
   old.]

   1. Old; long established.

   It is an inveterate and received opinion--

   2. Deep rooted; firmly established by long continuance; obstinate; used
   of evils; as an inveterate disease; an inveterate abuse; an inveterate
   course of sin.

   3. Having fixed habits by long continuance; used of persons; as an
   inveterate sinner.

   4. Violent; deep rooted; obstinate; as inveterate enmity or malice.

                INVET'ERATE, v.t. [L. invetero, to grow old.]

      To fix and settle by long continuance. [Obsolete or little used.]
